metadata.name: lilium #17
metadata.description:
lilium is a remix of my piece for day 9 of genuary 2023, prompt "Plants". it uses a series of force-directed graph layouts to produce a bouquet of flowers. inspired by Jared Tarbell's Happy Place.

press "c" to capture a screenshot at the current resolution. if you'd like a screenshot at a particular resolution, you can press "r" and a prompt will appear that will let you select a fixed resolution. you can either provide a single number like "1080" or a series of two numbers like "1080x2160". you can also provide a fixed resolution in the url with the "?resolution=..."

metadata.name: CA Monti #117
metadata.description:
As a sequel of previous collection CA Vista but with a completely different approach, CA Monti intends to explore landscape generation through the use of Stephen Wolfram's cellular automata.

Press 'S' to download.

metadata.name: CA Panico #152
metadata.description:
Third chapter of the trilogy dedicated to Stephen Wolfram's cellular automata.
 
Compared to CA Vista and CA Monti, CA Panico aims to further abstract the concept of landscape using CA rules in a more massive way.

The great variety of CA rules that controls the coloring and textures, noise influence, division into quadrants, chance of having glitches and outages all combined with 25 palettes and 5 different formats means that the outputs will be very varied and peculiar.

Press 'S' to download, you can zoom downloaded output to enjoy all the details.

metadata.name: Pixel Plus #85
metadata.description:
I took inspiration from retro video games and pixel art in this style but added a modern twist by incorporating intricate details and designs.
I separated and carefully arranged the pixels to form intricate patterns, shapes, and images. And I gave the effect a distinctly retro feel by using limited colors and blocky pixels to create creativity and imagination.
The result is a visually striking piece that captures the viewer's attention with bold colors, sharp edges, and meticulous attention to detail. Each pixel is carefully placed to create depth and texture, resulting in a nostalgic and contemporary work of art.
Made by p5.js
s = save

metadata.name: Hashing Things Out #20
metadata.description:
At some point in the lifetime of a workshop demonstration sketch, the sketch may mature to an actual "work" that transcends its original purpose as a simple exercise to test things out.

The variations of these geometric configurations are determined by your unique wallet address, such that minting multiple iterations of this generative token from the same wallet would give you identical outputs each time.

In this specific sketch, the stroke color, the number of vertices in the shape, and position of each vertex are all determined by your unique identity (wallet address).

metadata.name: CA Panico RGB #110
metadata.description:
Another tribute to Stephen Wolfram and his cellular automata, that's a reworking of my previous CA Panico collection.

In this version the RGB basic colors reign supreme, every single color is set by a cellular automata formula, giving life to interesting and particular textures and patterns.

Press 'S' to download.

metadata.name: Xel #52
metadata.description:
We’ve always known wallet addresses as strings of letters and numbers—dry, soulless data, yet always present.  
We decided to transform this constant presence into a living image.  
Instead of remaining mere tools for transactions, these addresses are turned into unique, enduring works of art—digital fingerprints that forever belong to their owners. A signature that always stays with its creator.

In a world where everything began with pixels—from the first games to the earliest digital artworks—we chose to reimagine your digital identity through pixels, intertwining the spirit of pixel art with the structure of the wallet itself.  
As a result, each pixel creature born in this project is generated directly from the structure of the wallet address (fxminter) and the artwork's hash (fxhash).

Each creature in this project is a synthesis of these two unique data points.  
Colors, forms, and even the sequence in which the creature appears are entirely derived from them.  
The piece begins with an intelligent system analyzing your identity.  
Then, these data are translated into pixel creatures, built in three distinct sections, emerging with colors extracted from the hash.  
No two creatures are alike—each is a living, one-of-a-kind reflection of its holder.

But this is only the beginning...

Holders of tokens from this project (Season One) will unlock a hidden layer within their artwork—one that is not visible at first glance.  
It’s as if an abstract image, a subconscious imprint, rests quietly behind the pixels.  
A layer that will only be revealed with entry into Season Two.

This piece marks the first season of a long-term project—one crafted with a multi-season perspective.  
With each season, not only do the meaning and form of the artworks evolve, but the value of the tokens increases over time—not just in visual terms, but as fragments of a living narrative, where each season uncovers a new layer of *you*.

Only the holders of Season One tokens will possess the key to enter Season Two.

Reptile 🦎
----------
Made by p5.js

metadata.name: overloaded #281
metadata.description: Overloaded attempts to be a system to explore time perception, through non-representative images, while still representing pixels as upscaled forms. It plays with permanence and non-permanence.

metadata.name: Cymru #97
metadata.description:
Inspired by the rolling hills, lakes and beaches of Wales backdropped by mountains, Cymru is a gentle, peaceful, fully generative artwork referencing a collage of soft pastels on textured paper.

Use number keys to render at different sizes.

metadata.name: ukiyo-e seascape #351
metadata.description:
Generative seascape (or lakescape) inspired by ukiyo-e art.
The art is programmatically drawn using basic shapes, easy math, random and noise. (except text typography)

February 2022
ykxotkx

metadata.name: The Rifting #46
metadata.description:
Generative artwork inspired by the effects of plate tectonics.
*click and wait for the music to fade in

There are four different rifts with 'Basin & Range' being the rarest.

The song is called 'The Rifting' originally released in 2018 by my alter ego 'Polynia'.
It was made by sampling some tape loops with an Akai S1000,
then playing the samples with a midikeyboard, finally recording an improv with a Tascam 4-track tape recorder.

You can find it here:
https://polynia.bandcamp.com/track/the-rifting
or on all streaming platforms.

Created with Hydra
hydra.ojack.xyz

Genesis artwork by pxlshrd
Twitter: @pxlshrd

A vivid and surreal depicting of lush fields i'm longing to be inside of.

metadata.description:
Tezumie are interdimensional beings who seemingly spawn out of thin air. Tezumie are obsessed with Eating, fighting, and Collecting junk they find throughout the universe. Once a Token is minted, you will spawn your very own Tezumie! 

Beware, there is more to them than they let on. They are not Restricted to the blockchain, and you may notice strange things appearing and disappearing around you. You have been warned.
